Let’s analyze this wonderfully archaic sentence. It’s a plea, delivered in a deliberately formal and somewhat antiquated style – a characteristic of Early Modern English. The core of the sentence revolves around filial duty and the speaker’s responsibility to care for his father. Consider thou myne condicyon;



The sentence employs several stylistic devices to achieve its effect. Notice the extensive use of polysyllabic words – “condicyon,” “reflecte,” “destytute,” “penurye,” “rendere,” “litter,” “yeolde.” This creates a sense of solemnity and emphasizes the gravity of the situation. Reflecte upon myne fader.



The sentence structure is complex, with multiple subordinate clauses and inversions. Phrases like “Shall I forsake hym” and “when it lyeth wythin my poure” are characteristic of the period’s formal prose. It’s a deliberate attempt to sound weighty and authoritative. Consider thou myne condicyon;



The vocabulary is deliberately old-fashioned. Words like “blyndnesse” (blindness) and “destytute” (poor) evoke a sense of vulnerability and hardship. The repetition of “myne” emphasizes the speaker’s personal involvement and concern. Reflecte upon myne fader.



The rhetorical question – “Shall I forsake hym?” – is central to the sentence’s argument. It’s not a simple inquiry; it’s a challenge to the listener to consider the moral implications of neglecting one’s father. Consider thou myne condicyon;



The sentence’s overall tone is one of earnest pleading and moral obligation. The speaker is not simply asking for assistance; he’s demanding it, based on a deeply held sense of duty. Reflecte upon myne fader.
